A considerable part of Seneca’s works is lost, portions of those which we have and others entirely, to which allusions are made either in his own extant writings or by other authors. Among the more interesting of them ap- pear to have been the De Situ et Sacris Aqusptiorum, which was one of the fruits of a temporary residence in Egypt during his early life, the Dc Forma M ancli, in which, ac- cording to a reference in Boethius, there is stated a theory of the spherical shape of the earth, and the Dialoqus de Super- stitione, to which St. Augustine alludes in his De Civitate

, Dei (VI. 10), besides several other moral essays. Seneca ’ also wrote a biography of his father, and various published ‹ Epistulae now lost, to say nothing of important addresses

which he prepared for Nero, and the uncounted speeches which he produced in his practice as an advocate. The alleged correspondence between Seneca and St. Paul, as well as several of the works which were credited to Seneca in the Middle Ages, are now known to be spurious.²
